Omics Workflow

Bryan Stanfill & Dan Fortin

December 12, 2017

The goal of this document is to go show by example the workflow used to analyze “omics” data using the pmart suite of R packages. To do this we consider a small data set provided by Janet Jansson that is compose of 18 soil samples in total from 3 sites (A, B, C) located in Kansas. For each site, 6 samples were collected and 3 treated with glycine (“Plus”) while the other 3 were left untreated (“Neg”). There were 3 biological replicates for each site/glycine combination. For proteomics data, there were some technical replicates as well. There are also data at the lipid, metabolite, metagenome and metatranscriptome levels, but we focus on the protein level data. The process is the same regardless of which “omic” data set is considered.

Before analysis, the pmartRqc package is used to prepare the metabolite data. A general workflow possible with the pmartRqc package is summarized in the following graphic for generic biomolecules, e.g., metabolites, proteins, peptides.

The proteomic data is given to us as raw abundance values for each peptide and each of the 18 samples. Typically raw abundance data is transformed to make them more amenable to modeling, e.g., log base 2 scale.

Format data

Formatting the data consists of two steps. First we group the samples based on the treatments of interest. In this case we’re interested in the “site” and “treatment” variables so each “Group” variable is a combination of those two things. The following Table is the first few lines that maps sample to group.

metab_data <- group_designation(omicsData = metab_data, main_effects = c("site", "treatment"), time_course=NULL)
groups <- groups_orig <-  attr(metab_data, "group_DF")
colnames(groups) <- c("Sample Name","Group","Treatment","Site")
knitr::kable(head(groups))

A_Neg_rep1 Neg_A Neg A
A_Neg_rep2 Neg_A Neg A
A_Neg_rep3 Neg_A Neg A
A_Plus_rep1 Plus_A Plus A
A_Plus_rep2 Plus_A Plus A
A_Plus_rep3 Plus_A Plus A

We then consider different transformations of the data. The following histograms summarize the metabolite abundance distributions on different scales for the first replicate of a sample take from site A without the glycine treatment. In this scenario we proceed with the log base two transformed data.

sampi <- metab_data$e_data[,"A_Neg_rep1"]
raw_hist <- qplot(sampi,bins=100)+xlim(c(0,1e7))+xlab("Abundance")+theme_bw()
trans_l2 <- qplot(log2(sampi),bins=100)+xlab(expression(log[2](Abundance)))+theme_bw()
trans_l <- qplot(log(sampi),bins=100)+xlab(expression(ln(Abundance)))+theme_bw()
gridExtra::grid.arrange(raw_hist,trans_l2,trans_l,nrow=1)

#The function `edata_transform` will transform the data to the scale of interest
metab_data <- edata_transform(omicsData =  metab_data, data_scale = "log2")

To compare the abundance distributions across samples, box plots of abundance distributions for each sample are plotted.

bplot_df <- reshape2::melt(metab_data$e_data[,-1])
qplot(variable,value,geom='boxplot',data=bplot_df,fill=I('#33CCFF'))+xlab("")+ylab(expression(log[2](Abundance)))+
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=45,hjust = 1))

Filtering

Next, metabolites that don’t meet certain criteria are filtered, i.e, removed from the dataset. Several types of filters are available and their use depends on the scientific question of interest and future analysis plans. The filtering methods available in the pmartRqc package are

  • Degenerate biomolecule
  • Coefficient of variation
  • IMD-ANOVA filter
  • Custom filters

Because we’ll be using IMD-ANOVA to test for differential abundance of metabolites across samples, we use the IMD-ANOVA filter, which performs both ANOVA and IMD filters. The ANOVA filter removes metabolites that don’t have at least two observations per group, i.e., the minimum number of observations needed to estimate a variance. The IMD filter removes metabolites that don’t have at least three observations within one group, which is a good rule of thumb as the “theoretical number of observations of a metabolite that any single group must have to be significant in the absence of observations in any of the remaining groups” (Webb-Robertson et al. 2010 first paragraph, page 4). For this dataset, no metabolites were filtered out.

imd_afilt <- imdanova_filter(omicsData = metab_data)
metab_data <- MSomics_filter(filter_object = imd_afilt, omicsData = metab_data, min_nonmiss_anova = 2,min_nonmiss_gtest = 3)
#attr(metab_data,"filters")

Once specific metabolites are filtered out, samples can be filtered out as well. Typically, samples are only filtered out if they are believed to be of suspicious quality. rMD-PAV is the only sample filter currently available in the pmartRqc package. rMD-PAV uses each samples’ biomolecule abundance distribution to assess samples that do not fit in with the rest of the data. The rMD-PAV scores can be compared to a \(\chi^2\) distribution to get \(p\)-values associated with the null hypothesis that each sample belongs with the rest of the data versus the alternative that that sample is an outlier.

rmd_filter_res <- rmd_filter(omicsData = metab_data)
metab_data <- MSomics_filter(filter_object = rmd_filter_res, omicsData = metab_data, pvalue_threshold = 0.0001)
to_remove <- attr(metab_data,"filters")$rmdFilt$filtered

In this example, the third replicate in the glycine negative group at site B (B_Neg_rep3) was filtered out because it returned a \(p\)-value less than the specified threshold, 0.0001. The four metrics used to determine outlyingness are plotted in the following plot, the red point is the sample that was deemed to be an outlier.

rmd_stats <- rmd_filter_res[,c("sampleID","MAD","Kurtosis","Skewness","Corr")]
rmd_melt <- reshape2::melt(rmd_stats,id.vars=c("sampleID"))
bad_egg <- dplyr::filter(rmd_melt,sampleID==to_remove)
qplot(NA,value,data=rmd_melt,geom='boxplot')+facet_wrap(~variable,scales='free',nrow=1)+
  geom_point(aes(NA,value),colour=2,data=bad_egg)+xlab("")+theme(axis.text.x=element_blank())+ylab("")

Normalize data

After the data are group, transformed and filtered, they are normalized in order to account for systematic bias due to experimentation, sample preparation and instrumentation (Callister et al. 2006). Side note, see Bell et al. (2010) for a new normalization technique pointed to metabolites in general and applied to an experiment with Arabidopsis thaliana. Here we used median centering to normalize the metabolite abundance data. That is, the median abundance for each sample is subtracted from the observed abundances such that the result abundance distribution for each sample has a median value of 0.

median_center <- function(e_data, edata_id, feature_subset, backtransform=FALSE){
  subset.data <- e_data[as.character(e_data[,edata_id]) %in% as.character(feature_subset),]
  subset.data <- subset.data[, -which(colnames(subset.data)==edata_id)]
  subset.data <- as.matrix(subset.data)
  # get medians per sample to use for normalization
  location_param <- apply(subset.data, 2, median, na.rm=TRUE)
  scale_param <- NULL
  # normalize
  med.diff <- e_data[,-which(colnames(e_data)==edata_id)] - matrix(rep(location_param, each=nrow(e_data)), nrow=nrow(e_data))
  # if backtransforming, subtract subset median from each sample (updated  by KS 9/29/15)
  if(backtransform==TRUE){
    med.diff <- med.diff + array(median(subset.data, na.rm=TRUE), dim=dim(e_data[,-1]))
  }
  norm_data <- data.frame(e_data[,edata_id], med.diff)
  names(norm_data)[1] <- edata_id
  return(list(norm_data=norm_data, location_param=location_param, scale_param=scale_param))
}
norm_e_data <- median_center(e_data = metab_data$e_data, edata_id="Metabolite",feature_subset = metab_data$e_data$Metabolite)
metab_data$e_data <- norm_e_data$norm_data
attr(metab_data,"data_info")$norm_method <- "median_center"
attr(metab_data,"data_info")$location_param <- norm_e_data$location_param
attr(metab_data,"data_info")$scale_param <- norm_e_data$scale_param

Summarize data

The final functionality of pmartRqc is summarization. A quick tabular summary of the final product gives a few statistics that are often of interest. In particular the number of samples, metabolites, missing observations and the proportion of missing observations.

attr(metab_data,"data_info")$num_emeta <- 0
summary(metab_data)

Summary of 'metabData' Object
---------------------------                                 
Unique sampleIDs (f_data)      17
Unique Metabolites (e_data)   126
Rows (e_meta)                   0
Missing Observations            3
Proportion Missing          0.001

To summarize the data visually, one can create a correlation heatmap to identify which samples are highly correlated. Also, a probabilistic principal component plot, which can be used to identify possible groups of data. In this example, the data group in the \(x\)-axis by site, indicating that the site variable is the single most influential variable in the data. There is no clear pattern in the \(y\) direction.

d_for_cor <- cor_result(metab_data)
corr_plot <- plot(d_for_cor)+coord_fixed()+theme(legend.title=element_blank(),axis.text.x=element_text(angle=45,hjust = 1))+
  ggtitle("")
d_for_pp <- dim_reduction(metab_data,k=10)
pp_plot <- plot(d_for_pp)+coord_fixed()+geom_point(size=3,aes(colour=treatment,shape=site))
gridExtra::grid.arrange(corr_plot,pp_plot,nrow=1)

Analyze data

To test for differential abundance between groups we use the IMD-ANOVA test. The independence of missing data (IMD) tests for qualitative differences between groups while analysis of variance (ANOVA) tests for quantitative differences between the groups. The package pmartRstat includes functions to implement IMD-ANOVA that allows for covariates, groupings and other effects.

Because we’re interested in testing for differences in treatments (positive versus negative for glycine) while controlling for differences due to different sites, the “site” variable is treated as a covariate. After controlling for differences in sites, differential abundance between treatments is tested for.

Two plots that summarize the results are below. The first is a bar chart that illustrates how many metabolites are deferentially expressed between the two treatments after accounting for differences in sites The “direction” indicator signifies if the metabolites are expressed at a higher (up) or lower (down) rate in the test group (plus glycine) relative to the control group (negative glycine). The second figure is a volcano plot, which plots the fold change in abundance (on the log scale) against \(p\)-values for the IMD and ANOVA tests. Because there were so few missing observations, the test for missing data has a \(p\)-value very close to 1 for all metabolites. Results for the ANOVA, however, show that a few metabolites are deferentially expressed with large fold changes, while other metabolites have large fold changes but are not statistically significant. This is due to the noise of those metabolites, that is, the test group may be under expressed relative to the control group, but that metabolite is subject to a lot of noise and is therefore not statistically significant.

library(MSomicsSTAT)
metab_data <- group_designation(omicsData = metab_data, main_effects = c("treatment"), time_course=NULL)
cov_df <- metab_data$f_data[,c("sampleID","site")]
def_comp <- data.frame(Control="Neg",Test="Plus")
all_groups <- imd_anova(metab_data,test_method = "comb",covariates = cov_df,comparisons = def_comp)
colnames(all_groups$Full_results)[7] <- "P_value_G_Plus_vs_Neg"
plot(all_groups,plot_type = c("bar","volcano"),fc_threshold = 2)
